column168: Shipment consists of 3 large, grey totes; the rest of the items are household goods.  Screener viewed the totes by x-ray and noticed the outline of an aerosol can.  Screener opened tote and found one 13.75 oz. aerosol can of Sprayon - food grade white grease.  DG agent on shift looked up SDS and  confirmed this to be fully regulated hazmat.  Shipment put on hold, DG report filed with airline hazmat management team, and photos taken.  FAA clearance is dependent to their inspectors' schedules.
column169: This, like most undeclared hazmat recently, was found in a Club 49 shipment.  There needs to be more literature sent to customers about cargo rules for shipping.  Many customers believe what is accepted in baggage is also acceptable as cargo.  More needs to be done to educate our customers, before they walk in the door and before the leave the facility.

column168: After leaving the hump, a release was discovered from the PRD on tank car NDYX130729 possibly due to a hydraulic surge..  No product impacted the ground.  The PRD did not reseat properly.  Upon inspection and adjustment by a contractor the valve properly reseated.  Shipper obtained OTMA-3 for movement.

On June 4, 2019 at 0245 EST, XPO Terminal (XTM) experienced a hazardous cargo release. It was reported that when terminal personnel was unloading the trailer they notice (1) 55-gallon of " UN1814, POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE, SOLUTION, 8, PG II, ERG 154" leaking from the top of the drum.  The spill is contained in the middle of trailer #3113248 floor. Due to the terminal having no overpack waste containers a contractor was dispatched. Contractor arrived onsite and confirmed material released was  Stripper 4C in a  55-gallon poly drum. Approximately 1-2 gallons have impacted a 4' x 6' area of the trailer floor and pallet. They do not see any visual damage to drum, possibly the lid does not have a good seal and the liquid sloshed out. They have overpacked the drum in a 95-gallon poly drum. They applied Spill-X caustic neutralizer to the impacted areas, the sweepings were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. Waste generated was staged in OS&D for terminal to manage proper disposal.

The TILX 111624, empty residue hydrochloric acid,  was reported leaking acid from the protective housing while the car was in the RIP track at the PTRA North Yard at approximately 0700 hours on June 3, 2019.  Slick Response was notified to respond to the track and inspect the car.  Slick personnel opened the protective housing and found that all four bolts on the liquid line were loose and could be tightened by hand allowing residual product in the tank to push out. They also found two of three bolts on the fill hole cover less than tool tight. Slick secured all bolts to tool tight specifications, neutralized the acid on the sides of the tank car and the ground, then pressure washed the car. The cause of the non-accidental release (NAR) was due to the car not being properly prepared for transportation, several bolts on the liquid line and fill hole were less than tool tight.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: While enroute to a customer, Univar's driver made a left hand turn from Ryders Lane in East Brunswick on to southbound Cranbury Road in East Brunswick when a passenger vehicle got the Univar driver's attention.  Passenger vehicle driver informed Univar driver that his load was falling out of his trailer.  The driver pulled over and saw the damage to the rear roll up door caused from a 55 gallon drum of 50% caustic soda that had fallen off of a pallet in the trailer and rolled into the back door of the trailer. The bottom panel of the back door was broken open and the drum was partially out of the trailer.  The drum developed a hole which caused 50% caustic to drip out of the drum and out of the trailer. The driver called his dispatch, and a clean up crew was sent from the Morrisville branch to assess the situation and clean up the spill.  In the mean time, the driver used paper towels to contain the spill and prevent the 50% caustic from entering a near by storm drain.  Once the drum leak was stopped, we were able to gain access to the trailer and determined that the load strap that was securing the drums to the side of the trailer had been pulled out of the rib in the wall of the trailer which caused the strap to loosen and allow the drum to fall off the pallet and damage the trailer door. Local police (Officer S. Clayton) and County Haz-Mat (Chief C. Prott) were notified.  By the time they arrived that drum leak was contained and the spill was mostly cleaned up.  Approximately 10 - 15 gallons of 50% caustic was lost.  County Haz-Mat helped transfer the damaged drum to a over-pack container and verified that none of the 50% caustic had entered the storm drain.  At that point, County Haz-Mat considered the scene clear and left.  Local police stayed to make sure the transfer of the remainder of the load in the damaged trailer to a different trailer was done safely.  Once that was done, local police and fire considered the scene clear and everyone left.  Traffic was never stopped on the roadway. No one was hurt in the incident, and no tickets or citations were issued.

column168: FAIR SKIES, SUNNY DAY, DRY DIRT ROAD, MP 35.6 DALTON HIGHWAY, NORTHBOUND, LOADED WITH 6,500 GALLONS OF #1 HEATING OIL (DIESEL FUEL). DRIVER LEFT THE ROADWAY, TRIED TO CORRECT AND RETURN TO ROADWAY WHEN THE TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED OVER SKIDDED AND CRASHED. TANK SHELL WAS SEVERELY DAMAGED RESULTING IN LEAKAGE. THIS IS A REMOTE SECTION OF THE LOAD WAY WITH NO TO LITTLE TRAFFIC, NO CELL SERVICE OR FACILITIES NEAR BY. DRIVER DIED ON IMPACT AND PASSENGER (ANOTHER DRIVER EMPLOYEE) WAS KNOCKED UNCONSCIOUS. ONCE SOMEONE CAME ONTO THE SCENE WORD WAS SENT AS TO THE ACCIDENT AND WE WERE NOTIFIED AT APPROXIMATELY 1500 ON MONDAY JUNE 3RD. WITHIN A FEW HOURS WE HAD A SPILL RESPONSE CREW ON-SITE TO STOP THE LEAKAGE, REMOVE THE VEHICLES AND DEBRIS, AND CLEAN UP SCENE AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE WITHOUT HEAVY EQUIPMENT. WE ARE SENDING UP A EXCAVATION CLEANUP CREW WITH HEAVY EQUIPMENT FROM ALASKA ENVIRONMENTAL INC AND ALASKA INDUSTRIAL LLC REMOVE CONTAMINATED SOILS AND REPLACE WITH NEW SOILS AND RESEED.
column169: AT THIS TIME WE ARE STILL IN THE PROCESS OF CLEANUP AND INVESTIGATIONS. WE HAVE NO COSTS INVOLVED AT THIS TIME AS WE ARE STILLING COMPLETING THE CLEANUP. THERE WILL BE NO RETRAINING OF THE DRIVER DUE TO THE FACT HE PERISHED IN THE ACCIDENT. OTHER DRIVERS RUNNING THIS ROUTE WILL BE REMINDED HOW DIRT ROAD DRIVING REQUIRES DIFFERENT DRIVING TECHNIQUES AND EXPLAIN THEM TO THEM. EXPLAIN NOT TRYING TO CORRECT AND RETURN TO THE ROADWAY ONCE YOU HAVE LEFT IT DUE TO SLOSH IN THE CARGO TANK WHEN QUICK CORRECTIONS ARE MADE.

column168: TILX 101032 was pulled from Shell Chemical, Deer Park, facility on 6/7/19 and brought to the PTRA Pasadena Yard at approximately 2130 hours. On Saturday, 6/8 at approximately 1700 hours the car was observed leaking product from the manway while in track 014 in the Yard.  Shell personnel were contacted and dispatched SRS to the scene to investigate and remediate the spill.  Emergency response personnel found that product was leaking past the liquid line flange. Six of the eight bolts on the flange, although tool tight, were able to be tightened further to stop the leak.  SRS personnel also vented the pressure on the car to prevent future issues.  The car was released into service for movement to the customer, Eco Services, at 1915 hours. The car was spotted on 6/10 at 0300 hours with no further issues.
column169: Shell Chemical is investigating the issues with this series of cars.

column168: A Veolia employee was attempting a to move a pallet containing 4 x 55 gallon flammable liquid drums  using a forklift.  The forks on the forklift were raised too high when approaching the pallet.  This  resulted in puncturing a flammable liquid drum near the bottom of the drum, completely draining the contents of the package.  The forklift operator immediately turned the forklift off and notified the field supervisor and manager.  The three Veolia employees rushed to form spill containment using absorbent media.

column168: At approximately 1700 hours, a Safety Kleen Systems dock employee was off-loading a poly drum with drum picker, at which time, the top of the drum broke and causing the drum fall. The contact with the ground caused the drum to rupture releasing about 30 liquid gallons of material. Absorbent material was immediately put down, and the spent product was contained. An in-house response crew responded to the spill, donned the appropriated PPE, and cleaned up the spill. Spilled material and absorbent materials used to remediate the spill were properly packaged, marked, and labeled and sent for disposal
column169: An investigation into the spill incident revealed that the drum picker used to offload the container was improperly positioned on the top lip of the drum, which caused the drum to inadvertently release and fall to the ground below. The weight and force at which the drum impacted the ground caused the drum body to rupture resulting in the release. The dock employee was immediately ordered to refrain from any further forklift operations and retrained on the proper offloading techniques when using drum pickers.

column168: At approximately 0600 hours, a Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. warehouse employee discovered an in-transit storage tank trailer leaking into containment. Approximately 200 gallons of hazardous waste liquid spilled into containment. Absorbent material was immediately put down outside of the containment area to prevent spillage onto earthen ground bordering the containment area. An in-house response crew responded to the spill, donned the appropriate PPE, and cleaned up the spill. Spilled materials were pumped into another nearby empty tank trailer along with the remaining liquid in the compromised tank trailer. The Spilled material and absorbent materials used to remediate the spill were properly packaged, marked, and labeled and sent for disposal.
column169: An investigation into the spill incident revealed that the spillage occurred due to areas weakened by corrosion. The compromised tank trailer was immediately placed out of service and sent for repairs at an in-house maintenance facility.  Warehouse employees were retrained on proper tank inspections before the loading process.

The damaged original drums, spent absorbents, and other debris were containerized into (2) 85-gallon metal drums, (1) 85-gallon poly drum, and (4) 55-gallon metal drums.  The waste containers were then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: Train was stopped on a grade due a mechanical issue .  When train started to move multiple cars derailed and this car rolled 90 degrees.  While checking for flammable vapors before wrecking operation began, NS contractor found vapors leaking from the bread box on this car.  Investigation revealed the vapor valve was partially open, vapor valve stem worn enough as to not allow operation of the valve with the handle (which was laying in the bread box), the packing gland on the stem was loose, and the vapor line valve plug had bad threads.  Contractor was able to apply enough force with a wrench to tighten plug and tightened packing gland.

column168: SKIDS OF BATTERIES WERE IN THE NOSE OF TRAILER THEY WERE BANDED POORLY, WHEN THE TRAILER LEFT THE DOCK THE SKID IN THE NOSE BROKE FREE FROM THE PALLET AND TIPPED OVER ON ITS SIDE. column168: NRC Environmental responded and remediate the leaking paint. The release was estimated at 1 gal and the source was from one 5 gal pail that was loaded damaged. NRC over packed all affected material and removed it on behalf of FedEx Freight.  FDXU532517 was reported by the BNSF STOIMF hub as parked in the containment pit after deramping off rail car a& discovering unit was leaking a white paint like material. No paint was found on the rail car the unit arrived on. No harm or interference with Mainline, personnel nor the environment. There is no need for outside services or organizations to respond.  There was ~ 6 ounces on the concrete track side which is currently being cleaned up. LARS inspection of the unit found same white paint, appearing to be the UN1263 // PAINT RELATED MATERIAL 3 // PG II (from the waybill), leaking at the left front area of the container floor. There is ~ 6 ounces on the plastic under the container, leaking at a rate of 10 drops/minute. The LTL cargo was multi layered in 2 rows to the doors with some cargo/pallets fallen towards the rear. One cargo strap was observed as securement on 1 item. As such, this is a shipper responsibility incident due to insufficient securement, allowing the cargo to fall over.
column169: Shipper need to ensure that the cargo is properly secured for transportation to prevent spillage of hazardous materials in the future.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On June 12, 2019, at 11:56 hours, CSX personnel at the CSX Sibert Yard in Mobile, AL reported that CPDX 110088, a loaded tank car of liquefied petroleum gas, had vented from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Chevron Products Corp, was notified via CHEMTREC report 2019-0612-00177.  United States Environmental Services (USES), a CSX emergency response contractor, as well as personnel from Chevron responded to assess the car.  Response personnel performed both visual inspection of the car and air monitoring; no indication of a release was evident.  Additionally, the crew checked pressure and outage- 135 psig and 21” respectively.  At this time, it was also relayed that yard personnel had witnessed the suspected venting while coupling the suspect car during switching operations.  It was determined that the probable cause of the release was due to overhanding of the car causing hydraulic surge of the product which temporarily active the pressure relief device.  The car was released for transportation. Subsequently, on June 13, 2019, personnel at the CSX New Orleans Yard also reported CPDX 110088 to be venting from the top.  Specialized Professional Services, Inc. (SPSI), a CSX emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the yard and found the car to be venting from the pressure relief valve.  At this time it was suspected that the car had a faulty pressure relief valve.  SPSI contained the release with application of an emergency capping kit, transferred the lading to an empty tank car, and relieved all residual pressure on the empty car by vapor flaring.   SPSI’s certified mobile repair unit was then contracted by the car owner (Chevron) to perform replacement of the valve.  Upon removal of the Rego 8890 pressure relief valve, it was evident that the interior spring was broken.  A QA 7.1 will be filed.

column168: On June 19, 2019, at 0845 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal NML regarding a loose cap on top of (1) 5-gallon poly pail of Victory Sanitizer (Organic peroxide type F, liquid, UN3109). Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed that due to a reaction inside the container, the top of came off the container.  The contractor advised that there was no reaction occurring upon his arrival and no product release.  The contractor saturated the container top with water to confirm that there was no longer a reaction.  The drum was resealed.  The spent absorbents and other debris were containerized into (1) 55-gallon poly drum.  The waste drum was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED UNDERNEATH THE 100 BELT. WHILE THERE WAS NO RELEASE OUTSIDE THE BOX, THE PACKAGE SHOWED OBVIOUS DAMAGE FROM A LEAK WITHIN. UPON RETRIEVAL TO THE HAZMAT AREA BY DESIGNATED RESPONDER, THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED. AT FIRST, THERE IS A SEPARATE CORRUGATED LAYER AS A BUFFER, THEN FOUR JUGS, SEPARATED BY CORRUGATED PARTITIONS, LAY IN THE BOX. THESE JUGS ARE BUFFERED BY ANOTHER CORRUGATED LAYER UNDERNEATH. ONE JUG SHOWED APPARENT LEAKAGE. ALL FOUR CAPS WERE CHECKED AND THE CAP OF THE JUG THAT LEAKED WAS NOTICED TO BE LOOSE. THE REMAINDER JUGS WERE IN GOOD CONDITION AND UNTOUCHED BY THE SPILLAGE.

DONNED PPE AND TOOK SPILL CART TO PINK BELT FOR LEAKING PACKAGE. FOUND FLAMMABLE LIQUID BOX ON SLIDE LEAKING DOWN SLIDE. USED DECISION AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET TO CHECK FOR HAZARDS, USED UNIVERSAL ABSORBENT AND LINED SPILL TRAY TO TRANSPORT PACKAGE TO DAMAGE CAGE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS DRIVING ON NM-18 SOUTH OF JAL, NEW MEXICO AT 1:27 AM WHEN A DRUNK DRIVER HEADING NORTH WAS DRIVING IN OUR SOUTH BOUND LINE ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. THE DRUNK DRIVER THEN TRIED TO CUT IT BACK TO HIS LANE AND STRUCK OUR TRUCK CAUSING THE DRIVER TO LOSE CONTROL AND ROLL THE TRUCK AND TRAILER. THE DRIVER CALLED DISPATCH WHO THEN CALL THE SHERIFFS DEPARTMENT AND SUPERVISORS. THE TOP HATCH OF THE TANKER STARTED TO LEAK BECAUSE THE SEAL HAD BEEN DAMAGED, CONTAINMENT WAS BUILT AND BUCKETS AND SPILL PADS WHERE SET UP. WE HAD A SECOND TRUCK THAT WAS NEXT ON THE SCENE AND STARTED TO SUCK THE OIL OUT OF THE WRECKED TANK, THIS TOOK ABOUT 45 MINUTES. THE HIGHWAY WAS ONLY SHUT DOWN FOR ABOUT 30 MINUTES WHILE THE WRECKERS TIPPED THE TANKER BACK ON ITS WHEELS. THE CONTAINED AREA WAS THEN DUG OUT AND SAMPLES TAKEN.
column169: WE HAVE SET UP A DEFENSIVE DRIVING SIMULATOR TO COME TO OUR FACILITY AND FOCUS ON NIGHT TIME DRIVING. I FEEL THE DRIVER DID EVERYTHING HE COULD OF. HE STAYED IN HIS LANE AND WAS SLOWING DOWN, BUT BECAUSE IT WAS DARK THE GLARE OF THE CARS HEADLIGHTS AND THE CAR BEHIND THAT HE DID NOT SEE THE CAR WAS IN HIS LANE UNTIL IT WAS TOO LATE. TRAINING FOR OUR FIELD SUPERVISORS WILL CONTINUE BUT I BELIEVE THEY REACTED THE BEST THEY COULD HAVE TO REDUCE THE SPILL.

column168: On June 18, 2019 at 1125, Landstar trailer experienced UN3267, corrosive liquid, basic, organic, n.o.s., 8, PGIII release due to inadequate loading. Contractor personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of material released impacting a 54' x 8' area of the trailer floor and a 1' x 1' area of asphalt beneath trailer. The contractor utilized absorbents and simple green to clean impacted areas. The damaged containers and spent absorbents were containerized into a cubic yard box and transported to disposal facility on June 21, 2019. It was determined no drains, soils or waterways were impacted by the release.

column168: DESIGNATED RESPONDER DONNED PPE AND RESPONDED TO A REPORT OF DRY POWDER LEAKING FROM A BOX WHICH HAD BEEN PLACED ON EXTENDO BELT. PACKAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY IDENTIFIED AS HAZARDOUS/CORROSIVE BY MARKINGS/SHIPPING PAPERS. FOLLOWING DT AND CORROSIVE CLASS RS PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN LINED SPILL TRAY, ALL POWDER WAS SWEPT UP, ALL TRANSPORTED TO DMP STATION FOR PROCESSING. EMPLOYEE WAS TOLD TO WASH HANDS/GLOVES. AT DMP STATION PACKAGE WAS OPENED ENOUGH TO VERIFY CONTENTS AND DETERMINE CAUSE OF SPILLAGE. PACKAGE, CONTENTS AND SPILLAGE WERE DOUBLE BAGGED AND TRASHED PER WASTE DISPOSAL FOR VSQG DMP FACILITY. DURING BAGGING RESPONDER WAS EXPOSED TO NOAH DUST ENOUGH TO CAUSE ITCHING ON EXPOSED FOREARMS (MINOR INJURY), THEN WASHED SELF AND PPE PER DECONTAMINATION PROCEDURES.
column169: MULTI-LAYER PAPER BAG FAILED AT STITCHED CLOSURE. THERE WAS NO FILL MATERIAL BETWEEN BAG AND OUTER CARTON. BAG AND CONTENTS HAD ALL SLID TO ONE END LEAVING APPROX. 30% OF OUTER CARTON VOLUME UNFILLED AT OTHER END. OPINION: EXCESSIVE UNFILLED VOLUME IN OUTER CARTON ALLOWED PAPER BAG TO SHIFT DURING HANDLING; SHIFTING POWDER IN BAG CAUSED IT TO DISTORT AND THEN BURST AT PUNCTURES (STITCHING). SUFFICIENT FILL SHOULD BE USED BETWEEN OUTER CARTON AND BAG. STITCHED SEAMS IN BAG SHOULD BE REINFORCED WITH TAPE OR FOLDED OVER THEN TAPED.

THE TRACTOR/TRAILER WAS TRAVELING NORTH ALONG US-641 HAULING A LOAD OF 1.1D EXPLOSIVES WHEN THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AND BEGAN TO VEER OFF THE ROAD. HE ATTEMPTED TO CORRECT THE VEHICLE BUT RAN OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD AND OVERTURNED ONTO A UTILITY POLE CONTAINING THREE TRANSFORMERS. THE DRIVER EXITED THE VEHICLE, WITHOUT ANY INJURY, AND PROCEEDED TO CALL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS. THE CALLOWAY COUNTY SHERIFFS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED WITHIN 6 MINUTES AND BEGAN EVACUATIONS. THE DRIVER ALSO CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR WHO ACTIVATED THE COMPANY'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  ALTHOUGH THE CARGO WAS INTACT AND CONTAINED, THE AREA WAS EVACUATED DUE TO ELECTRICAL ARCING FROM THE TRANSFORMERS ONTO THE TRAILER CONTAINING THE EXPLOSIVES. BEFORE CLEANUP EFFORTS COULD BEGIN, THE NEARBY POWER LINES AND TRANSFORMERS HAD TO BE SAFELY NEUTRALIZED BY THE LOCAL POWER COMPANY. ACCURATE ENERGETIC SYSTEMS PROVIDED A TEAM OF EMPLOYEES TO ASSIST WITH OFFLOADING THE EXPLOSIVES FROM THE DAMAGED VEHICLE, EVALUATING PACKAGE SAFETY AND LOADING ONTO A NEW VEHICLE FOR TRANSPORT.  THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BUT SOME PACKAGES WERE REPLACED DUE TO PACKAGE DAMAGE SUCH AS RUPTURED EDGES (4-6" RUPTURES) AND CRUSHED CORNERS.
column169: AES WILL BE REVIEWING SAFE DRIVING PROCEDURES WITH ALL DRIVERS.

column168: The sequence of events leading up to and including the incident are roughly as follows: 1) A CT-500 trailer consisting of two modules was in the process of being filled by two drivers at the Santa Clara site. The CT-500 contains 49 DOT-SP-14576 specification vessels, each containing ~10kg.  These vessels are manifolded to effectively make a tube trailer. 2)  One of the two drivers, “driver 2”, reported leak in vicinity of the main isolation valve of module “A” 3) “Driver 1” told “Driver 2” to “shutdown A” so he could depressure the line to effect a repair.   4) “Driver 2” shut the manual isolation valve for Module A as well as operated control panel to shutdown the pump which was filling the trailer. The fill process stopped & all air operated valves on stanchion and trailer closed. 5) “Driver 1” then depressurized the line and disassembled several fittings to repair the leak. “Driver 1” believed the rear module was still being filled. 6) During the repair, “Driver 1” observed an issue with an O-ring and realized he could not fix. 6) During the repair, “Driver 1” observed an issue with an O-ring and realized he could not fix. 7) “Driver 1” instructed “Driver 2” to “shutdown the process” thinking that fill process was continuing. 8) Since the process was already stopped, the button available to press by “Driver 2” was the button to start the next filling activity.  9) This button prepares the trailer to be filled by opening the trailer automatic valves. 10) This button was pressed by “Driver 2”, opened the trailer valves, and pressurized the manifold with the compromised piping. 11) This led to a large release of hydrogen at the rear of the front module. 12) The hydrogen release ignited with a short delay, leading to a deflagration, overpressure, and subsequent fire. 13) The fire melted the fusible link air lines and closed the valves within a few seconds. The emergency stop was also pressed by “Driver 1” 14) Overpressure from the deflagration caused distortion and movement of vessels and piping. 15) These forces resulted in damage, leakage and continued fire, leading to subsequent PRD releases.  No vessels failed as a result of this incident. 16) The fire involved two adjacent trailers and four tractors, leading to tire and diesel involvement as well. Approximately 250 kg was released. No hydrogen was released from adjacent trailers. 17) The drivers left the area and the Santa Clara Fire Department responded to extinguish the fire.
column169: Improve driver fill procedure, to include disconnection of tractors during loading Reinforce proper protocols for performance of maintenance activity Improved training of drivers Meet with DOT and NTSB in August to discuss equipment regulations and possible improvements as a result of incident learnings. This is schedule for mid-August 2019

column168: On June 25, 2019, at 1713 ET, XPO Logistics terminal UTU located in Tucson, AZ, notified ERTS of a release of UN2734 "Chem Treat BL 1558" to the trailer. All waste was staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.

On June 21, 2019, at 0838 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal XAU located in Aurora, IL, notified ERTS of an approximate 2 cup release of NA1993 "UV 142" from a 345 gallon stainless steel tote. The waste was staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: Gold Star FS straight truck (cargo tank) released approximately 224 gallons of clear diesel fuel onto I-88 in proximity to Rock Falls, Illinois.  The vehicle was traveling west-bound when the driver noticed a mist coming from the truck.  Driver pulled over immediately and contact Gold Star FS management and EH&S.  An Illinois State Trooper in the vicinity noticed the stopped truck and invoked the local fire department/emergency response.  We understand that IDOT was also notified and coordinated lane closure during cleanup.  Approximately 120 bags of oil dry was utilized to cleanup an approximate 1.25 mile stretch of the interstate road surface (ER contractor Johnson Trucking, Sterling).  Additionally, the same ER contractor proceeded, at the direction of the IEPA ER, to excavate surface soils in proximity to where the truck had stopped due to dead and stressed vegetation observed.  Remediation efforts are completed excepting confirmatory soil sampling following remediation efforts and final reporting to the IEPA.  The outcome of final remediation efforts will be coordinated with the IEPA ER personnel (Chuck Curtis).   IEMA #H2019-0629

column168: SEVERAL CONTAINERS ARE IN A CARTON TO CREATE THIS 'KIT'. THE KIT IS MARKED WITH A LIMITED QUANTITY DIAMOND LABEL. A ONE GALLON CAN AND 4 OTHER METAL BOTTLES ARE IN THIS CARTON WITH NO OTHER CUSHIONING OR PACKAGING. NEITHER THE METAL CAN NOR THE METAL BOTTLES HAVE ANY KIND OF PROTECTION TO KEEP THE LIDS FROM LOOSENING DURING TRANSIT. THIS CARTON/KIT WAS THEN PLACED INSIDE OF A CARDBOARD CONTAINER FOR SHIPPING AND NO DIAMOND LABELS OR HAZARDOUS MARKINGS WERE PLACED ON THIS OUTER CONTAINER. THERE WAS NO VOID SPACE FILL OR CUSHIONING IN BETWEEN THE 2 CARTONS.
column169: LIDS ON INNER CONTAINERS NEED TO BE SECURED WITH CLIPS OR TAPE TO PREVENT CAPS FROM LOOSENING. PROPER CUSHIONING NEEDS TO BE PLACED IN BETWEEN CARTONS.

column168: On June 5, 2019, at 0040 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XNW regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to blocking and bracing in transit, (1) 4-gallon metal pail of Thurmalox Black Heat Resistant Coating (Paint, flammable, UN1263) spilled, releasing approximately 5 ounces of product on to the dock floor.  Terminal personnel cleaned up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The damaged pail, spent absorbents and other debris were containerized into (1) 10-gallon metal drum.  The waste drum was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

On June 12, 2019, at 0435 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal NPB regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a forklift puncture, (1) 10-gallon plastic pail of NP814 Armor Roof Copolymer Roof Coating (Flammable liquid, n.o.s., (xylene, aromatic petroleum distillates) UN1993) was damaged, releasing approximately 9 gallons of product on to the trailer floor. Contractors were dispatched to handle the release clean up.  The release was cleaned up with absorbents and the proper PPE.  The damaged container, released product and other debris were containerized in (1) 55-gallon metal drum.  The waste drum was then contained onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: While delivering fuel into underground storage tanks at the Murphy USA station a vehicle drove through coned off area and into our delivery hose and fitting which caused it to disconnect from the UST. Our driver immediately stopped the flow of product however approximately 20 gallons spilled.  The other vehicle fled the scene.  Our driver worked to contain and secure the spill area.  911 was called with fire and police personnel responding.  The fire department applied oil dry to the spill area.  Our driver was able to obtain the license tag number of the at fault vehicle and provided it to the police.  Our customer, Murphy USA was notified and assigned their emergency response contractor to the scene to perform the clean up of the area.
column169: This was a non-preventable incident on our part due to the other driver disregarding our secure work zone.

column168: THE RELEASE WAS A RESULT OF A FAULTY GAUGE ON DORMAN BEAN PLANT'S STORAGE TANK FOR ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. JR SIMPLOT EMPLOYEES WERE IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERRING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA FROM A MOBILE TRANSPORT TANK INTO DORMAN'S STATIONARY STORAGE TANK WHEN THE RELEASE OCCURRED. IT HAS BEEN DETERMINED THAT JR SIMPLOT EMPLOYEES OVERFILLED DORMAN'S TANK BECAUSE DORMAN'S FLOAT GAUGE WAS NOT READING A CORRECT AMOUNT. AS A RESULT OF OVERFILLING THE TANK, A PIPING FLANGE AND PUMP SEAL LEAKED PRODUCT FORM DORMAN'S PIPING; THE LEAK DID NOT OCCUR FORM THE SIMPLOT MOBILE TRANSPORT TANK. AN ESTIMATED 27,000 POUNDS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST AND VAPORIZED INTO THE ATOMSPHERE.  JR SIMPLOT EMPLOYEES IMMEDIATLEY SHUT THE MAIN VALVE ON OUR MOBILE TRANSPORT TANK BUT WERE UNABLE TO CLOSE THE EMERGENCY SHUTOFF VALVES ON DORMAN'S TANK. THEY CALLED 911 AROUND 11:55 AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO EMERGNECY SERVICES. EMERGENCY SERVICES ARRIVED ON SCENE SHORTLY AFTER AND WERE ABLE TO CLOSE THE VALVE ON DORMAN'S TANK AND STOP THE RELEASE  AROUND 12:20. EMERGENCY SERVICES DID SHUTDOWN HIGHWAY 24 AND WETS BOUND LANES OF I-70 TEMPORARY FOR A SHORT DURATION OF TIME (LESS THAN 30 MINUTES).  THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER #1248661, COLORADO DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT #2019-0318, AND KIT CARSON COUNTY LEPC.
column169: JR SIMPLOT COMPANY D.B.A. SGS BURLINGTON WILL BE IMPLEMENTING A PRE-FILL CHECKLIST TO PREVENT EMPLOYEES FROM FILLING CUSTOMER STORAGE TANKS THAT HAVE FAULTY GAUGES, PIPING, OR VESSELS. ADDITIONALLY, WE WILL BE UPDATING OPERATING PROCEDURES AND PROVIDING ADDITIONAL TRAINING.

column168: Initial conditions: Container GLDU 993405-1 was rejected from initial shipment due to bent j-bar and a hole through the door caused by the locking bar guide being damaged. Container was opened and it was noticed the cornerlashing had slipped up on the bags and the bags had shifted forward about 6 inches. 6/13/19 Innovative Repair facility Fife WA: Steve Hansen(TAM International), Juke Johns(Southern Ionics), and Damian Crespo(Cordstrap) went to Innovative Repair to reposition the bags and retighten the strapping. Incident 6/13/19@ 12:OOpm Innovative Repair facility Fife WA: When operator(Greg) was preparing to load pallet 5 into container, I noticed some sand on ground. Upon looking at bag, I noticed additional sand on pallet. I informed Greg we had a Ieaking bag and once it is placed into the ISO container, we need to stop. 2 piles were equivalent to 6 fl oz cup(1.3 Kg) between the 2 piles and a very small amount was trailed about 6 to 8 feet. Retrieved a shovel, bucket, and metal brush and cleaned up the visible sand. Due to the proximity of the container and the spilled sand, readings of the spill could not be taken until loading completed and container moved. A background survey was performed with 2 detectors- Background between 0.18 pSv/h/ 27 CPM and pSv/h/ 46 CPM. Survey after removal of material: 0.21 pSv/h/ 43 CPM to 0.30 pSv/h/ 47 CPM Removed material was placed in ISO container in a 5-gallon pail with lid. Seal applied to door. Leak from bag was either from contact with telehandler forks or plastic pallet tearing bag. Size of hole- 2 inches. column168: On June 27, 2019 at 1745 ET, Landstar Inway experienced an approximate 170-gallon UN1824 release. The release was a result of two 330-gallon poly totes being damaged due to tractor trailer accident. All release was reported to have impacted trailer floor and asphalt. Contractor was dispatched for remediation.  Contractor personnel arrived onsite and advised the tow company was unable to unload trailer due to not donning the proper PPE to handle the material per instruction by the Fire Department. Contractor personnel suited up in the required level A ppe to access one of the leaking totes located in front of the trailer that is releasing out of trailer in attempt to plug totes to prevent further release. The onsite tow company shifted the totes so Contractor personnel could gain access to inside of trailer. Contractor personnel confirmed approximately 170-gallons of UN1824, Sodium Hydroxide had released outside of trailer onto the asphalt and soil shoulder. Citric acid was applied to impacted areas to neutralize, absorbents were applied to impacted neutralized areas. Contractor personnel transferred recoverable material from damaged totes into new 330-gallon poly totes. It was reported the released material had saturated the trailer floor, unable to load the new totes into trailer. Contractor personnel applied neutralizer to trailer floor and absorbents to prepare the trailer to be moved to tow companies yard along with the new totes in order to re-open highway. Contractor provided a street sweeper, skidsteer and roll-off to remediate a 6’ x 140 yard impacted roadway. The initial response was completed and both lanes were re-opened. ALDOT requested a thin layer of absorbents be placed on the impacted areas. The impacted trailer was transported to contractors service center to finalize the cleaning. The recovered material in the two 330-gallon poly totes were rejected by consignee and will be deemed waste. The roll-off box of impacted debris, damaged totes and totes of recovered product will be scheduled for proper disposal upon profile approval.

column168: On June 27, 2019 at 0800 ET,  Ward Trucking reported an approximate 8-gallon UN1993 release. The release was a result of cargo being crushed due to improper loading. All release was reported to be contained to trailer floor. Contractor dispatched for cleanup. Contractor personnel arrived onsite and confirmed pallet of 10-kilogram metal cans containing UN1993. The release impacted a 1’ x 2’ area of the trailer floor. Contractor personnel applied oil-dry to impacted areas and impacted pallet was broken down. Contractor personnel broke down the pallet to determine the damaged cans and containerized twenty-five containers, the recovered spent material and impacted pallet pieces into five 55-gallon metal salvage drums. The generated waste was staged pending final disposal. The remaining twenty-three undamaged containers remained at location on a pallet.
The cause of the release was loose manway swing bolts.

column168: Sekhem Ward had issues loading at Del. City and the TO on duty bypassed the system/sensor and allowed him to continue to load which resulted in a small spill at the terminal. This was cleaned up by the driver and TO. After. loading, he arrived at the station, checked in with the manager on duty and obtained an initial veeder root tape. Mr Ward set up his cones to block off the unloading area, and attached the vapor hose to the ground and then to the truck. As he was attaching the vapor hose to the vapor recovery head, he noticed there was a small amount of product in the vapor recovery system and attempted to troubleshoot the issue, he then placed a spill pad under the vapor recovery system. After securing the vapor hose, he opened the internals and unloaded pot 1, and then as he moved on to pot 4, he noticed the trailer was unloading slowly. He walked the hose checking for any defects, and then the pot started to-unload at a faster rate. He then immediately noticed that there was a drip and spray out of the vapor hose- he immediately hit the emergency shutoff valve and contained the spill on the unloading area. Approximately 10 gallons of fuel spilled, and was cleaned up by the driver and the station staff. No fuel reached storm drains or retention ponds, and about 8 spill pads, 2 booms and 101bs of staydri were used to mitigate the spill.
column169: The driver and trailer were brought down immediately to Baltimore. The driver met with the Driver Support Team and was retrained on the loading and unloading process. He will spend the rest of the week in, on the truck training, with a.driver trainer and will have his BOL's closely monitored for the next month. The trailer was inspected and it was noticed that the emergency valve cable was out of Adjustment in compartment 4 which caused the trailer to offload slowly. The trailer will be degassed and a method 27 EPA vapor test and further inspections will be done and repairs will be made.

column168: On June 15, 2019 at 1830 EST, ERTS was contacted by personnel at Landstar Ranger regarding an over the road hazardous material release. It was reported that due to a cracked weld on a pipe on (1) 550-gallon metal tote of UN1992, Flammable liquids, n.o.s., 3(6.1), PGII (Contains Methyl Ethyl Ketone Dimethyl Disulfide), (Marine Pollutant) "EM Blend 4 Sulfur Solvent" approximately 7 gallons released to a 4' x 4' area of the trailer and soil. ERTS dispatched Environmental Restoration to respond. Due to heavy traffic and rain, the contractor did not arrive onsite until 0100 EST on June 16, 2019. The contractor located the tote and was instructed by the manufacturer to transfer the remaining product into 55-gallon metal drums. The remaining product was transferred into a total of (12) 55-gallon metal drums that were shipped onto the consignee. After transferring the product out of the tote into drums the contractor then confirmed that approximately 7 gallons of product released onto the trailer bed under the tote and was wiped with spill pads. pH strips were used to test the outside soil and came back neutral. Due to the rain, Environmental Restoration believes the product that released onto the soil washed away or evaporated. Based on the amount that was salvaged during the transfer Environmental Restoration confirmed a total of 7 gallons of product released. No cleanup was required for the soil. The contractor placed the spill pads used into a poly bag which was then placed inside (1) 55-gallon drum to be disposed of.

column168: We (Pioneer Tank Lines) picked up a consolidation load from Clean Harbors in Cannon Falls, MN on 6/17/2019. The load was brought back to our yard to be transported for Clean Harbors. While at the  yard, yard personnel noticed a leak coming from the trailer. upon inspection it was noticed there was  a leak in one of the barrels on the rear of the trailer. Clean Harbors was notified immediately along with the Minnesota Duty Officer and the Minnesota Department of Transportation. While waiting for Clean Harbors to arrive, Pioneer personnel applied absorbent pads to the area in and directly below the trailer on the escaped material. Upon Clean Harbors arrival they salvage packed the leaky drum. it was  investigated and found that the leaky drum had a nail hole punctured in it from a faulty pallet. the  leaked material was neutralized and absorbed and placed in salvage containers. the salvage drum  containing the compromised drum was filled with absorbent material, secured and checked for leaks.  absorbent material used for cleanup was placed in a separate drum for disposal.
column169: I believe that the faulty pallet was the main problem. it nail head was perfectly hidden making the damage unnoticeable until enough product had leaked. A Better pallet would have been ideal and proper training on what to look for as far as degrading pallets that could compromise packaging and/or product stored in the packaging. I would like to see the haz waste industry move to non wooden  pallets or at least pallets that are discarded or pulled from use with hazmat or hazwaste and not used. I have seen some pretty badly damaged pallets that are continually used for shipping hazardous  materials. Maybe its time for a pallet regulation.

column168: At 1851 EST, ERTS received a call from XPO Logistics (TERMINAL NAT)  regarding a hazardous cargo release.  It was reported that due to a forklift puncture, one 55-gallon poly drum containing UN3266, 8, PG II,  Branson IS released an approximate 25 gallons onto the trailer floor. Due to the size and type of the spill, ERTS dispatched a Contractor to tend to the over-pack and cleanup.   2044 EST - The Contractor arrived at the terminal and located the spill.  2048 EST - It was confirmed that due to a forklift puncture, an approximate 20 gallons of Branson IS Formulated Cleaning Concentrate spilled onto a 15'x8' area of the trailer floor and onto an 8'x10' area of the underlying asphalt. 2100 EST - The Contractor placed the damaged drum with remaining corrosive product into an 85-gallon poly overpack. Granular absorbents were utilized to clean and decontaminate all impacted areas. All waste was staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.
Associate punctured freight with forklift blades while loading / unloading causing product to leak

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: THE SITE WAS SHUT DOWN FOR THE EVENING PROPERLY AND THE PLANT WAS CLOSED AND UNMANNED AT THE  TIME OF THE EVENT.  AT 1823 THE ELIOT FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED REGARDING A POTENTIAL HIGH PRESSURE LEAK FROM THE ELIOT FACILITY. UPON ARRIVAL AND CONFIRMATION OF THE RELEASE THE FIRE DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED THE XNG OPERATIONAL CONTROL CENTER. XNG PERSONNEL WERE IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO THE ELIOT FACILITY. UPON ARRIVAL XNG PERSONNEL INSPECTED THE SITE AND FOUND THE ESD VALVE HAD FAILED TO CLOSE, DESPITE ACTIVATION OF THE ESD SYSTEM (AS PER SOP) PRIOR TO THE CLOSING OF THE SITE FOR THE EVENING . DUE TO THE FAILURE OF THE ESD VALVE THE HIGH OPERATING PRESSURE OF THE PIPELINE LEAD TO THE LIFTING OF THE PRV VALVE ON THE PLANT DRYER. THIS PRV FAILED TO RE-SEAT AND WAS THE SOURCE OF THE HIGH PRESSURE RELEASE.  UPON FINDING THE ESD VALVE INOPERABLE XNG PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE MAIN GAS INLET VALVE STOPPING ALL GAS FLOW FROM THE PIPELINE TO THE ELIOT FACILITY. THIS STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE ELIOT SITE REMAINED CLOSED  AND ISOLATED FROM THE GAS INLET UNTIL THE TIME AN OVERHAUL COULD BE COMPLETED ON THE ESD AND PRV VALVES THAT FAILED. THE SITE WAS REOPENED AFTER REPAIR AND TESTING OF THE VALVES HAS BEEN COMPLETED.
column169: XNG HAS COMPLETED A FULL OVERHAUL OF BOTH THE MAIN EMERGENCY SHUTDOWN VALVE THAT FAILED TO CLOSE, AS WELL AS A FULL OVERHAUL OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE THAT FAILED TO RESEAT. IN ADDITION XNG HAS IMPLEMENTED A CHANGE TO THE STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE FOR THE SHUTDOWN OF THE ELLIOT FACILITY. OPERATORS MUST NOW MANUALLY VERIFY THAT THE MAIN ESD VALVE IS CLOSED PRIOR TO DEPARTING FOR THE EVENING.

column168: PACKAGE FOUND IN MIDDLE OF TRAILER

AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 PM ON THE LAWNSIDE DAY SORT. UNLOAD SUPERVISOR OPENED TRAILER AND WAS HIT BY A STRONG ODOR. THE ODOR WAS VERY STRONG AND STARTED TO MOVE INTO SURROUNDING AREAS SO IT WAS DECIDED TO REMOVE TRAILER OFF OF THE DOOR AND PLACE OUTSIDE. THE RESPONDER RESPONDED AND FOLLOWING DECISION TREE DONNED SCBA TO CLEAN UP SPILL. THE ODOR WAS VERY STRONG AND IRRITATING TO THE SURROUNDING AREA AND IN TRAILER THAT IT BECAME DIFFICULT TO WORK AROUND EVEN WITH SCBA. IT WAS DECIDED TO MOVE TRAILER FARTHER AWAY FROM BUILDING AND AN OUTSIDE RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED. RAPID RESPONSE ARRIVED AND CLEANED UP SPILL AND TRAILER AND PLACED EVERYTHING IN DRUMS. ABOUT 8 OTHER PACKAGES WERE AFFECTED BY THE LEAKIER AND HAD TO BE DISPOSED OF BY RAPID RESPONSE DUE TO STRONG ODOR.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0230 ON JUNE 8, 2019 A TRAILER CAUGHT FIRE WHICH ORIGINATED FROM THE BRAKES ON RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND CONSUMED MOST OF THE AUTOMOTIVE PARTS AND ACCESSORIES BEING DELIVERED TO AUTOZONE STORES IN THE SALT LAKE CITY UT METROPOLITAN AREA. THE INCIDENT OCCURRED NEAR I-84 MM 209 THE TRAILER ORIGINATED FROM THE AUTOZONE DISTRIBUTION CENTER IN PASCO, WA. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO PUT OUT THE FIRE WITH THE IN CAB EXTINGUISHER BUT THE BRAKES WE TOO HOT.  PRODUCT PACKAGING ONLY FAILED AS A RESULT OF THE FIRE. AS A PART OF THE CONTAINMENT BY FIREFIGHTERS, PORTIONS OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SEEPED INTO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY. OUR PROVIDER, 3E, WAS CONTACTED TO OBTAIN A CREW TO CLEAN UP EASILY ACCESSIBLE SPILLAGE. AUTOZONE IS WORKING WITH THE CLEANUP TEAM TO DETERMINE IF THE AREA IS ON INDIAN TRIBAL LAND. ONCE DETERMINED, WE WILL TAKE THE APPROPRIATE ACTION TO REMOVE THE AFFECTED SOIL. NO WASTE ENTERED A WATERWAY.  INVESTIGATION OCCURRED ON THE TRAILER ONCE AUTO ZONE HAD ACCESS TO THE EQUIPMENT. IT APPEARS THAT POTENTIALLY A SLACK ADJUSTER FAILED CAUSING THE BRAKES TO LOCK UP CAUSING EXCESSIVE HEAT WHICH LED TO THE FIRE. AUTO ZONE REVIEWED ALL MAINTENANCE RECORDS. IN JANUARY, REPLACED FOUR SETS OF BRAKE DRUMS, PADS AND KITS; THE SLACK ADJUSTER WORKED PROPERLY. THE AIR HOSES AND BRAKE VALVE WERE REPLACED LATER IN THE SAME MONTH THE SLACK ADJUSTER WORKED PROPERLY. IN MARCH, THE BRAKES WERE ADJUSTED NO ISSUE WITH THE SLACK ADJUSTER IDENTIFIED. NO ISSUES WERE IDENTIFIED IN THE ANNUAL PM CONDUCTED ON MARCH 25, 2019 NOR WHEN BOTH RIGHT REAR TIRES WERE REPLACED DUE TO WEAR. ADDITIONALLY, THE DVIRS WERE REVIEWED AND NO INDICATION BY ANY DRIVER THAT THERE WAS AN ISSUE WITH THE SLACK ADJUSTER.
column169: AUTOZONE FOLLOWS ALL DOT REQUIRED INSPECTIONS AND WITH TRAILERS, CONDUCTS AND ANNUAL INSPECTION AT EACH 90 DAY INTERVAL. AUTOZONE CONTINUES TO REVIEW MAINTENANCE PROCESSES TO MEET OR EXCEED DOT REQUIREMENTS AND MITIGATE EQUIPMENT ISSUES.

column168: Clean Harbors technicians arrived on site for scheduled lab pack and regular bulk was pick up.   Technicians checked in at reception and met with EHS Specialist.  Technicians proceeded to lab pack  and load waste onto truck.  During the loading process, the technician struck the drum on the lip of the liftgate resulting in a puncture to the drum.  The technician immediately laid the drum on its side with  damaged area in the up position.  This minimized the spill amount.  Absorbent material was put down,  storm drain spill valve confirmed closed and the area blocked off.  Emergency response team assembled The response team verified the leak had stopped.   It was also verified the liquid had evaporated, but left a stain on the dock.  The drum was overpacked for continued transportation.  The stained area was  cleaned using a pressure washer.  The area continued to be washed until there was no more dye visible in the wash water.
column169: While this is human error, it is certain the drum dolly used for the poly drum was not the correct one. The customer has since purchased the correct drum dolly for these specific drums.  The Clean Harbors technicians have since been retrained to identify the proper dolly to be used for poly drums.  As well, to implement their stop work authority in the event the tools they're using are not the correct ones.

column168: On June 14, 2019, at 0810 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XTN regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to improper loading, (1) 55-gallon metal drum of DOWTHERM™ A Heat Transfer Fluid (Environmentally hazardous substances, liquid, n.o.s., UN3082) was punctured, releasing approximately 2 liters of product on to the trailer floor.  Terminal personnel cleaned up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE.  The punctured drum, spent absorbents and all other debris were containerized in (1) 85-gallon metal drum.  The waste drum was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: ON JUNE 10, 2019, AT APPROXIMATELY 7:15 P.M. CDT, A TRACTOR-TRAILER OPERATED BY FREEHOLD CARTAGE WAS PARKED AT THE ABOVE REFERENCED LOCATION WHEN THE UNIT OPERATOR NOTICED A LEAK COMING FROM THE TRAILER AND A SLIGHT ODOR. FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED, ONE (1) 275-GALLON TOTE OF GLACIAL ACRYLIC ACID HAD BEEN DAMAGED DUE TO A DAMAGED VALVE. AS A RESULT, OF THE DAMAGED VALVE APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS WERE RELEASED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR. FREE PRODUCT SLOWLY DRIPPED FROM THE TRAILER AND IMPACTING THE CONCRETE SURFACE.

column168: UPON PULLING ONTO OUR IN-HOUSE SCALE. ANOTHER ASSOCIATE NOTICED LIQUID COMING FROM THE CENTER SPILL DAM OF TANKER 135. IT WAS VERIFIED THAT THE DOME WAS CLOSED IN A SECURE FASHION, BUT THAT THE GASKET FAILED. BASED ON THE EMPTY WEIGHS FROM THE CUSTOMER AND THE LOADED WEIGHTS, THE DETERMINATION WAS MADE THAT APPROXIMATELY 68 GALLONS WERE LOST IN THE DRIVEWAY OF THE FACILITY. THAT VOLUME WAS CONSISTENT WITH WHAT WAS CLEANED UP BY OUR IN-HOUSE CLEANUP TEAM.
column169: OUR MAINTENANCE FACILITY BEGAN A CAMPAIGN TO INSPECT ALL DOME GASKETS ON OUR TANKERS. SPECIFICALLY THE TANKER INVOLVED WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE AND SENT IT FOR ITS ANNUAL HM-183 INSPECTIONS WHERE ALL GASKETS WERE REPLACED.

column168: On June 25, 2019, at 0632 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XDM regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a forklift puncture, (1) 275-gallon poly tote of Paint Loc CP Phosphatizing Agent (Phosphoric acid, solution, UN1805) was damaged, releasing approximately 275 gallons of product on to the trailer and dock floors, and continuing on to the asphalt beneath the trailer.  A contractor was dispatched to clean up the release with absorbents, neutralizer and the proper PPE.  The released product, damaged tote, and all other debris were containerized in (14) 55-gallon poly drums.  The waste drums were then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

column17: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY
column168: AT 0238 HOURS ON JUNE 18, 2019, KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY'S (KCS) ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED THAT A CREW REPORTED TANK CAR ACFX 220500 LEAKING IN THE KCS BEAUMONT, TX RAIL YARD. A RAILROAD QUALIFIED RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS MOBILIZED TO INVESTIGATE AND PERFORM AIR MONITORING.  UPON INVESTIGATION, THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED EMANATING FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD). AN IMMERSION TEST OF THE RETAINING CAP WAS PERFORMED AT WHICH TIME BUBBLES WERE OBSERVED, INDICATING THAT THE LEAK WAS LIKELY ORIGINATING FROM THE RETAINING CAP "O" RINGS. A "GAGGING" DEVICE WAS INSTALLED ON THE PRD TO TEMPORARILY SECURE THE CAR TO PREPARE FOR AN O-RING REPLACEMENT. ONCE NEW "O" RINGS WERE OBTAINED, RESPONDERS REMOVED THE "GAGGING" DEVICE. THE RETAINING CAP WAS REMOVED FROM THE VALVE, AND THE "O" RINGS WERE REPLACED. THE RETAINING CAP WAS REINSTALLED ONTO THE VALVE. AN IMMERSION TEST WAS PERFORMED, CONFIRMING NO LEAKS WERE PRESENT. CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE "O" RINGS REVEALED THAT THE "O" RINGS WERE FLATTENED, AND THE STEM GUIDE "O" RING HAD A SMALL DEFORMITY/CUT.  WHILE PERFORMING CORRECTIVE ACTIONS, THE RESPONDERS OBSERVED THE MAGNETIC GAUGING DEVICE CAP WAS WELDED TO THE GAUGING DEVICE FLANGE. BECAUSE THIS MODIFICATION RESULTED IN THE TANK CAR BEING OUT OF SPECIFICATION, KCS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER OBTAIN AN OTMA. ONCE THE OTMA WAS OBTAINED, THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.
column198: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY

column168: During routine facility inspections, facility personnel identified a compromised container. In appropriate personal protective equipment, verified through the internal health and safety department, facility personnel were successful in repackaging the material into authorized UN rated containers appropriate for the material. The release was contained to the warehouse floor with no impact or threat to land, soil, water ways or storm drains. The container were shipped their final destination without further incident.

column168: It was reported that two 50-pound plastic bags containing UN1823 Bulk Titrating Solution 11 were torn during loading operations. Approximately 1 quart of material was released onto the concrete dock floor. Terminal personnel cleaned the release and containerized the damaged bags. No drains or waterways were impacted by this release.

On June 18, 2019 at 2000 EST, Schneider Bulk Carriers experienced a 10-gallon release of UN3266, Corrosive liquid, basic, inorganic, n.o.s., (Sodium hydroxide, sodium hypochlorite), 8, PGII "EXELERATE CIP" from a three compartment tanker truck due to the bolt of the compartment leaking from what appeared to be a mechanical failure. ERTS dispatched Environmental Management Alternatives out of St. Louis, MO to respond for clean up. At 0048 EST, the contractor arrived on site and confirmed that a 25'  x 15' area of the asphalt and gravel had been impacted and that approximately 30 gallons of product was contained in several 1-gallon and 5-gallon pails by the driver. The contractor placed granular absorbents on the impacted asphalt and swept all spent absorbents into (1) 55-gallon poly drum. On June 19, 2019 at 0215 EST, the transload tanker arrived on site. At 0310 EST, the contractor confirmed that the transfer was completed with the truck pump and hoses. They successfully transferred 540 gallons of product into the new trailer. It was confirmed that they other two compartments would not need a transfer as their compartments were not releasing any material. Due to the impacted to the gravel, it was confirmed that the contractor would dispatch a skid steer to complete the clean up. At 1130 EST, the contractor with the skid steer arrived on site and began setting equipment up. Absorbents were placed along the soil edge as a precautionary measure however, the soil was not impacted by the release. Granular citric acid was placed onto the impacted area of gravel to absorb and neutralize. By 1330 EST, excavation activities had begun and the impacted gravel was placed into (5) 55 gallon poly drums and deemed non-hazardous due to being neutralized per the contractor. It was confirmed that the material did not seep deep into the gravel because the gravel was a hard road base material. At 1500 EST, the contractor departed site with all waste to dispose of. There were (6) 55-gallon poly drums of waste generated, one was liquid state classified as hazardous and the other five were solid state classified as non-hazardous.

column168: On June 19, 2019 at 0949 EST, ERTS was notified by Trimac personnel regarding a release of UN1866, Resin Solution, 3, PGIII "C909-AVB-05" due to an unspecified mechanical failure. The caller stated they would need a contractor to respond for cleanup. At 1325 EST, Taplin Environmental arrived on site and confirmed that approximately 50 gallons of product had released from the tanker truck due to a mechanical failure impacting a 3000 sq foot area. They reported that some product was intermittent due to being tracked by tires. Granular absorbents were placed on the area and containerized into (4) 55-gallon poly drums. The contractor placed more granular absorbents and left them on the impacted area overnight to absorb more oily residue. An additional (2) 55-gallon poly drums of liquid waste product were generated. The contractor departed site at 1530 EST. On June 21, 2019 at 0927 EST, the contractor advised that they had returned to the site and generated an additional (3) 55-gallon poly drums of absorbents totaling (6) 55-gallon poly drums of solidified waste and (2) 55-gallon poly drums of liquid waste. All waste was taken off site by the contractor for them to dispose of.

column168: A Superior Carriers isotanker carrying UN1247 Methyl Methacrylate was involved in a single vehicle rollover accident on I-40. Approximately 3 gallons of product was released onto the median. The local fire department and police shut down I-40 in both directions for 12 hours due to the hazardous nature of the material. The fire department sprayed down the area with foam. The material was transferred into a new isotanker. Absorbent booms were placed in the culvert in the median to collect any residual product.   The absorbent booms were collected at a later date. Air samples were collected with a 4-gas meter that showed no contamination remained on the site.

On June 12, 2019 at 0743 EST, ERTS was notified by ESTES personnel regarding a hazardous cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading, that multiple 1-gallon poly pails of UN1789, Hydrochloric acid, 8, PGII were damaged and releasing. ERTS dispatched New England Disposal Technologies to respond. At 0900 EST, the contractor arrived on site and confirmed that approximately 3-gallons of product had released to the trailer floor and asphalt impacting an 8' x 18' area. The contractor used bi-carbonate to neutralize and absorb the released product. The damaged pails, spent absorbents and impacted debris were all placed into (7) 30-gallon poly drums and two cubic yard boxes. The contractor left all waste on site at the terminal.
column169: Loading employees retrained on proper hazmat securement procedures.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column43: Valspar MS45 BLACK 2K URETHANE HS ENAMEL
column168: On June 27, 2019, at 0200 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal NCH notified ERTS of an approximate 1 quart release of UN1263 "Valspar MS45 BLACK 2K URETHANE HS ENAMEL" from a 55 gallon metal drum. Terminal personnel stated the release occurred due to a forklift puncture and was contained to the trailer floor. ERTS determined terminal personnel could clean the release. Terminal personnel donned PPE and contained and cleaned the release. The damaged drum and impacted absorbents were containerized into an 85 gallon poly drum and staged on site in the terminals waste area for terminal personnel to manage.
Hopper Car had crack in welds at seams of A & B Compartments allowing product to release. A & B Compartments were off loaded and leak stopped once empty.
column169: Proper inspection before loading, unloading, and before releasing for shipment.

column168: On June 27, 2019, at 0339 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal XPB notified ERTS of an approximate 2 cup release of UN1210 "NC 540 PMS 305 Blue" from a 5 gallon metal pail. Terminal personnel stated the release occurred due to improper loading as the pail fell releasing to the trailer floor. ERTS determined terminal personnel could clean the release with the appropriate provided PPE. Terminal personnel containerized the damaged pail and impacted absorbents into a 15 gallon metal drum which was staged on site in the terminals waste area for terminal personnel to manage.

A 55 gallon steel drum containing UN3266 foam brite fell over in a trailer. The drum released 2 quarts of product, over a 4 hr period,  from a worn O ring on the bung cap. The spill was contained inside the trailer. A hazmat contractor was dispatched for cleanup and overpacking operations.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On June 29, 2019 at 1132 EST, ERTS was notified by Landstar personnel regarding a hazardous cargo release. The caller stated that the product was believed to be UN1805, Phosphoric Acid, 8, PGIII. The tractor trailer was a local Flying J and requested a contractor be dispatched to conduct cleanup operations. Due to issues dispatching other contractors who would then cancel, ERTS finally had a successful dispatch for Kary Environmental who arrived at the site at 1547 EST. The contractor stated that approximately 28-gallons of UN1805, Phosphoric Acid, 8, PGIII had released from (1) 55-gallon poly drum due to a small pinhole puncture. This release had impacted a 53' x 8' area of the trailer as well as a few 1' x 1' areas of the asphalt parking lot were impacted. It was confirmed that less than 1 gallon of product had released out of the trailer. The trailer was neutralized with spill fighter then granular absorbents were used. The neutralized absorbents were placed inside (4) 55-gallon poly waste drums. The damaged 55-gallon poly drum was over packed into (1) 95-gallon poly over pack waste drum. The contractor successfully decontaminated the trailer and all cargo. The trailer was reloaded and the contractor departed site on June 30, 2019 at 0325 EST with all waste generated.

On June 20, 2019, at 0415 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal XSL notified ERTS of an approximate 1 cup release of UN1719 " Xaimeter OFS-0772 Siliconate" from a 55 gallon metal drum to their dock floor due to a forklift puncture. ERTS determined terminal personnel could clean the release with their provided PPE. Terminal personnel containerized the damaged drum and impacted absorbents into an 85 gallon metal over pack. The waste waste staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.

AT 1240 ON JUNE 9TH 2019 THE 0759 EH WAS SHOVING WEST UP 3 EAST APPROACH AND COLLIDED AT THE TOP OF THE HUMP WITH THE 0630 EAST HUMP ASSIGNMENT WHO WAS IN THE PROCESS OF HUMPING WESTWARD OFF OF 01EAPR. NO ONE WAS INJURED FROM THIS INCIDENT HOWEVER THERE WAS A TOTAL OF FOURTEEN CARS DAMAGED OF WHICH 10 OF THE CARS WERE DERAILED OF THE DERAILED CARS SIX OF THEM WERE ON THEIR SIDE JUST TO THE NORTH OF THE EAST HUMP LEADS AT THE TOP OF THE HUMP. MOST OF THE DAMAGED EQUIPMENT WERE TANK CARS IN WHICH TWO OF THEM CLASS 9 HAZARDOUS (DAMAGE TO OUTER SHELL OF ONE AND SAFETY APPLIANCES OF OTHER) HOWEVER THERE WAS NO PRODUCT THAT WAS EXPOSED FROM THE DAMAGE. IMMEDIATE AREA WAS CLEARED FOR INSPECTION. BEDFORD FIRE WAS CALLED TO SCENE AND NO ACTION TAKEN DUE TO NO RELEASE.
column169: DUE TO HUMAN RELATED INCIDENT, ADDITIONAL TRAINING AND REVIEW OF OPERATING PROCEDURE TO SEE IF CHANGE IS NECESSARY IS BEING COMPLETED.

column168: We picked up a pallet of boxes that our customer requested to be stacked and palatalized for transit. When my warehouse staff were re-stacking the cartons they noted 3 in the middle that are marked Class 3, and 1 carton marked limited quantity. We were not notified that we were transporting or being offered hazardous materials.   We then notified our customer and they continue to hold the 4 boxes at our facility and moved the rest of the cartons that were non-hazardous to Seattle on 7/8/2019

column168: Package was discovered leaking during the morning inspection. After donning appropriate PPE local personnel entered the vehicle to assess the situation. Absorbents were placed both inside and outside the vehicle and a portable berm was placed to catch and contain any further leakage, The material was removed from the damaged tote and collected in appropriate containers which were marked, labeled  and shipped to their final destination without further incident.
column169: Personnel have been retrained in container inspection and closure as well as thorough post-trip inspections

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: While unloading the trailer, the driver bumped the side of the drum with the tips of the drum dolly. The tips of the  dolly had become sharpened from repeated use causing the puncture. The trailer was moved from the dock to the  containment pad to control leakage. An in-house crew responded and cleaned up the spilled product from the inside of the trailer and asphalt dock area. No soil or waterways were impacted. The damaged package was over packed and shipped to its original destination without further incident.
column169: Drivers have been retrained in proper material handling and equipment inspection to prevent recurrence

column168: PDC IS STILL INVESTIGATING TO DETERMINE THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE K061 SPILL INCIDENT. THE DRIVER CLAIMS HE DETECTED A MOTORCYCLE OUT OF THE CORNER OF HIS EYE AND BELIEVED IT WAS APPROACHING HIS LINE OF TRAVEL QUICKLY, WHICH REQUIRED THAT HE SUDDENLY AND FORCEFULLY ACTIVATE HIS BRAKES. THE PDC HEALTH AND SAFETY DEPARTMENT AND HUMAN RESOURCES DEPARTMENT ARE REVIEWING ALL THE PERTINENT FACTS, AS WELL AS A VIDEO OF THE INCIDENT, TO ASSESS THE POTENTIAL ROOT CAUSE(S) OF THE INCIDENT. THE DRIVER HAS BEEN SUSPENDED FROM WORK WITHOUT ANY PAY SINCE JUNE 13, 2019, AS PDC CONDUCTS ITS INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT, AND WHAT DISCIPLINARY ACTION IS APPROPRIATE, IF ANY.  PROXIMATE CAUSES OF THE INCIDENT INCLUDE: THE TRUCK DRIVER ACTIVATING HIS BRAKES ABRUPTLY AS HE NEARED THE INTERSECTION WHERE THE SPILL OCCURRED; THE BRAKES PERFORMING AS DESIGNED AND ABRUPTLY STOPPING THE TRACTOR TRAILER COMBINATION; THE ABRUPT STOP CAUSING THE K061 CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER TO SHIFT FORWARD TOWARD THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER; THE VELOCITY OF THE SHIFTING K061 CARRYING IT UP THE FRONT WALL OF THE TRAILER WITH ENOUGH FORCE TO CAUSE A TEAR IN THE WELL-SECURED TARPAULIN; AND A QUANTITY OF THE KO61 EXITING THROUGH THE TEAR AND LANDING ON THE PAVEMENT WITHIN THE INTERSECTION. TO COMPOUND THE SITUATION, THE DRIVER DID NOT FOLLOW HIS TRAINING AFTER THE SPILL OCCURRED, WHICH ALLOWED VEHICLES TO DRIVE THROUGH THE SPILLED MATERIAL.
column169: THE PDC HEALTH AND SAFETY DEPARTMENT IS ALREADY MODIFYING THE CONTENT OF THE PDC DRIVER TRAINING TO MAKE THE PROCEDURES DISCUSSED ABOVE MORE EXPLICIT AND ROBUST. SPECIFICALLY, THE PERTINENT SECTIONS OF THE TRAINING DOCUMENTS THAT INSTRUCT DRIVERS TO USE THEIR TRUCK AS A BARRICADE AFTER A SPILL, AND TO PREVENT VEHICLE TRAFFIC THROUGH THE SPILLED MATERIAL, WILL BE PRESENTED WITH GREATER EMPHASIS AND DETAIL. EVENTUALLY AND ON THE EARLIEST POSSIBLE DATE AFTER THE ENTIRELY OF THE CONSEQUENCES AND TOTAL COST OF THIS INCIDENT ARE KNOWN, THEY WILL BE INCLUDED IN THE TRAINING MATERIALS AS EXAMPLES OF THE IMPORTANCE OF THE DRIVER'S ACTIONS AFTER A SPILL. PUT SIMPLY, PDC WILL DO EVERYTHING POSSIBLE TO USE THIS INCIDENT AS A TOOL TO IMPROVE FUTURE DRIVER TRAINING AND RESPONSE TO ANY SIMILAR INCIDENTS.

REAGENT CHEMICAL CARGO TANK WAS STOPPED AT RAILROAD CROSSING WHEN A FEDEX TRACTOR TRAILER RAN INTO THE BACK OF THE CARGO TANK. THE ACCIDENT CAUSED A PUNCTURE OF THE CARGO TANK, CAUSING THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION THAT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED TO RELEASE ONTO THE GROUND. THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES AND IT WAS A COMPLETE RELEASE OF THE LADING. RESPONSE FOR CONTAINMENT AND REMEDIATION WAS CONDUCTED BY INDIANA SPILL RESPONSE COMPANY, WHICH INCLUDED THE NEUTRALIZATION OF THE RELEASED MATERIAL AND REMOVAL OF THE IMPACT GROUND.
column169: ADDITIONAL TRAINING OF DRIVERS TO OBSERVE ALL OTHER TRAFFIC ON ROADWAY TO BE ABLE TO TAKE EVASIVE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT OF AN UNEXPECTED EVENT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column14: EXIT RAMP STATE ST TO I-94 W
column168: ON 6/3/2019 THE DRIVER PICKED UP A LOAD OF TEN TOTES WITH CORROSIVE LIQUID (CLASS8) FROM PIDC, 4788 RUNWAY BLVD, ANN ARBOR, MI TO 3M COMPANY AT COTTAGE GROVE, MN. THE LOAD WAS LOADED FROM THE SHIPPER AND SECURED BY THE DRIVER WITH LOGISTICS STRAPS AND EXTRA LOAD BAR. HE HAS STARTED DRIVING ON HIS WAY TO THE RECEIVER. AFTER TWO MILES, ON THE RAMP OF STATE STREET TO I-94 W, ALL OF THE SUDDEN THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER. I RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM A FIRE FIGHTER. HE INFORMED ME ABOUT THE ACCIDENT. HE ASSURED ME - NO OTHER VEHICLES AND PEOPLE HAVE BEEN INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT AND THE DRIVER WAS NOT INJURED. HE EXPLAINED TO ME THERE WAS SPILLED LIQUID - THREE OF THE TOTES WERE LEAKING. I CONFIRMED - THE COMMODITY IS TEN TOTES OF CORROSIVE LIQUID UN3264 (LLANTHANUM-YTTRIUM) 8. IMMEDIATELY I CALLED ENVIROSERVE (EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY) TO TAKE CARE OF THE SPILL AND SAFETY AROUND THE ACCIDENT AREA. AFTER THAT I CALLED THE SHIPPER. ENVIROSERVE AND THE SHIPPER TRANSFERRED THE LIQUID FROM THE LEAKING THREE TOTES AND FROM THE INTACT SEVEN TOTES TO NEW TOTES. THEY STORED THEM IN THE WAREHOUSE OF PIDC (SHIPPER). ENVIROSERVE ABSORBED THE SPILL AND CLEANED IT UP FROM THE ACCIDENT AREA. THEY WILL DO ALL ANALYZES AND TESTS TO BE IN COMPLIANCE WITH DEQ. THE SAME TIME CHEMTREC WERE SUPERVISING THE ACTION TAKEN FOR THE TRANSFERRING OF THE CHEMICAL, SPILL CLEANING AND SECUREMENT. THE ACCIDENT HAS BEEN REPORTED TO DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND NRC. PICTURE AND DIAGRAM ATTACHED.
column169: I WILL REQUIRE ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO THE DRIVERS OF THE COMPANY. REGARDING SECUREMENT AND TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, INCLUDING COMPLIANCE SEMINAR.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column62: Human Error; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON 6/12/2019 DRIVER WAS TRAVELING WEST ON HWY 72 IN FREDRICKTOWN, MO. AT 13:15 WAS TIME OF OCCURRENCE, EMPIRE ENERGY WAS NOTIFIED BY FIRE/EMS RESPONSE AT 13:45PM AS DRIVER COULD NOT LOCATE HIS PHONE AT THE TIME. FROM THE DRIVER STATEMENT, HE HAD ANOTHER VEHICLE COMING TOWARDS HIM ON THE NARROW HIGHWAY, HE MOVED OVER TO MAKE MORE ROOM, AND WAS ON THE SHOULDER AND THE TIRE WENT OFF THE ROADWAY TOO FARM WHICH CAUSED HIM TO HIT A CONCRETE BARRIER, WHICH OVERTURNED THE TRUCK, AND THE TRAILER. ENVIRONMENTAL WORKS WAS DISPATCHED OUT TO THE SCENE TO HELP WITH CLEAN UP REMEDIATION OF THE SITE WITHIN 2 HOURS OF NOTIFICATION. RON HERRYGERS P.G. WITH HERRYGERS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS ALSO DISPATCHED AND WAS PROVIDED AS A CONSULTANT THROUGHOUT THE CLEANUP. FUEL WAS LEAKED OUT NEAR BARNES CREEK IN FREDRICKTOWN, MO. SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED TO THE IMMEDIATE AREA, USING BOOMS AND EQUIPMENT FROM THE FIRE/EMS CREW AS A COMPARTMENT WAS DAMAGED DUE TO THE OVERTURNED TRAILER.
column169: DRIVER WAS COUNSELED AFTER INCIDENT, AN INTERNAL INVESTIGATION WAS COMPLETED AMONGST OUR OFFIC, AND FOUND THAT HUMAN ERROR WAS CAUSE, DRIVER WAS RELEASED BACK TO WORK.

column25: MARKWEST UTICA MIDSTREAM AND RESOURCES, LLC
column168: The Advantage Tank Lines, LLC driver was attempting to load condensate onto the tank trailer and failed to properly bleed off the pressure from one of the hoses.. When he disconnected the hose, the pressure that remained in the hose forced some residual condensate onto the ground. Environmental Products and Services of Vermont responded to the scene and handled the remediation. No further environmental impact is anticipated.
column169: Advantage Tank Lines, LLC will continue to train and enforce safe loading/unloading policies and procedures.

column168: The Kenan Transport, LLC driver was attempting to deliver diesel fuel into the customer's storage tank. In the course of doing so, a vehicle drove through the coned off delivery area and struck the hose adapter. The impact forced the hose adapter to become dislodged from the storage tank and approximately 20 gallons of diesel fuel was released. The local fire department responded to the scene and handled the remediation. No further environmental impact is anticipated.

column168: The Petro Chemical Transport, LLC driver was attempting to pump diesel fuel from the customers storage tank onto the tank trailer. In the course of doing so, he overfilled one of the compartments on the tank trailer causing approximately 10 gallons of diesel fuel to be released. A small amount of the released diesel fuel was able to migrate to a nearby storm drain. TAS Environmental responded to the scene and handled the remediation. No further environmental impact is anticipated.
column169: Petro Chemical Transport, LLC will continue to train and enforce safe loading/unloading policies and procedures.

column168: REDI SERVICES TRAILER #R218 WAS LOADED AT THE BALD MOUNTAIN MINE WITH CARBON BAGS ON PALLETS. THE LAST PALLET ON THE END OF THE TRAILER WAS OBSERVED TO BE DAMAGED AFTER BEING LOADED. THEY RE-POSITIONED THE PALLET AND SECURED IT WITH TWO STRAPS. THE LOAD LEFT THE MINE AND WAS TRAVELING ON STRAWBERRY ROAD HEADING TO EUREKA, CARLIN WITH THE DESTINATION ENDING AT THE REDI SERVICES YARD IN SPRING CREEK. ALONG THE WAY THE DRIVER HEARD A LOUD "BANG" AND STOPPED TO INVESTIGATE. HE OBSERVED HIS RIGHT REAR TIRE WAS FLAT. AT THIS TIME HE DID NOT SEE ANY O THE CARBON BAGS LEAKING BUT NOTICED THE BAG ON THE RIGHT REAR OF THE TRAILER WAS LEANING. HE AGAIN RE-POSITIONED THE BAG AND SECURED IT AND CONTINUED ON.   THE SPILLED CARBON FROM THE TOP OF THE SINGLE DUFFLE TOP BAG WAS FOUND DOWN MIDDLE OF THE ROAD AT THE INTERSECTION OF STATE ROUTE 892 AND COUNTY ROAD 73 (GRAVEL ROAD) EAST TO WARM SPRINGS RANCH. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED  KG-BM SECURITY ABOUT THE SITUATION. KG-BG SECURITY INVESTIGATED AND DISCOVERED THE SPILLED CARBON ON THE ROAD, AT WHICH TIME REDI-SERVICES WAS CONTACTED TO USE A VACUUM TRUCK TO COME AND PICK UP THE CARBON. column169: SHIPPER IMPROVEMENTS: KG-BM WILL REVISE THE INTERNAL STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE FOR LOADING CARBON. KG-BM WILL RE-ENFORCE TRAINING WITH CREWS INVOLVED WITH THE LOADING CARBON. column168: THOMAS HEATH, DRIVER FOR DAVID J MANNING TRUCKING, ENTERED THE CARSON TERMINAL AT 5:06 A.M. ON JUNE 3, 2019 TO LOAD JET FUEL FOR DELIVERY TO DLA-AMERICA WEST NAVAL WEAPONS CENTER. AT 5:23 A.M. IN LANE 6, HEATH ENTERED A 2,300 GALLON PRESET ON LOADING ARM 0603 TO LOAD JET-A FUEL IN HIS FIRST COMPARTMENT. WHEN THIS LOAD IS COMPLETED, HEATH ENTERED 1,600 GALLON PRESET TO LOAD JET-A FUEL IN HIS SECOND COMPARTMENT. WHEN THIS LOAD IS COMPLETED, HEATH ENTERED 1,700 GALLON PRESET TO LOAD JET-A FUEL IN HIS THIRD COMPARTMENT. AT 5:38 11 A.M., FIRE CAN BE SEEN EMANATING FROM INSIDE THE TANK AND OUT TWO TANK MANHOLE/UPPER COVERS IMMEDIATELY PRIOR TO THE TANK EXPLODING. [HEATH HAD LOADED 581 GALLONS OF JET-A WHEN THE EXPLOSION OCCURRED AND THE LOADING FLOW WAS AUTOMATICALLY SHUT OFF.] HEATH AND DRIVERS ON SITE IMMEDIATELY BEGAN TO EVALUATE TOWARD SEPULVEDA BOULEVARD. 911 IS CALLED AT APPROXIMATELY 5:40 A.M. THE EMERGENCY SHUTDOWN SWITCH FOR THE TRUCK RACK IS TRIGGERED; FIRE SUPPRESSION SPRINKLERS AND FOAM ARE ACTIVATED ; AND KINDER MORGAN PERSONNEL DIRECT FIRE MONITORS TOWARD THE FIRE. THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS DISPATCHED AT 5:41 A.M. AND ARRIVED ONSITE AT 5:50 A.M. THE FIRE IS EXTINGUISHED AT 6:10:26 A.M. THE EXPLOSION AND FIRE SIGNIFICANTLY DAMAGED THE TRUCK RACK AND FUELS LOADING SYSTEMS; THE EXPLOSION AND FIRE DESTROYED THE TRUCK AND TANK TRAILER IN LANE 6; THE TRUCK IN LANE 5 WAS DESTROYED, AND ITS TRAILER SEVERELY DAMAGED; AND FIRE AND EXPLOSION DAMAGE TO OTHER NEARBY TRUCKS WAS ALSO NOTED (AIR BRAKE LINES DESTROYED, ETC.).

column168: On June 26, 2019, at 0245 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal XNW contacted ERTS to report an unknown hazardous chemical release inside of a trailer. The caller advised that the odor was too strong for terminal personnel to access the trailer to unload freight or observe the release. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup and over packing operations. At 0930 EST, contractors arrived on site and confirmed (4) 5 gallon pails containing UN1133 Flammable Adhesives, 3, PG II fell during transit. The release impacted an 8' x 20' area of the trailer floor. The pallet was re-stacked and wrapped. The damaged pails were containerized into a 95 gallon metal drum which was staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.

DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AVIATION FUEL AT THE U OF U HOSPITAL FOR AIR MED, THE UNLOADING WAS A PUMP OFF USING OUR TRUCK PUMP. THE TANK TRAILER BEING USED WAS A TWO COMPARTMENTED TRAILER WITH A DOUBLE BULK HEAD SEPARATING THE TWO COMPARTMENTS. THE DRIVER COMPLETED UNLOADING COMPARTMENT TWO AND WAS SWITCHING TO COMPARTMENT ONE. THE DRIVER HAD ALREADY OPENED PRIOR TO HIM HOOKING UP THE HOSE TO THE LOAD HEAD. THE DRIVER PULLED THE DUST COVER OFF THE LOAD HEAD AND THE PRODUCT STARTED TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE LOAD HEAD VALVE AND STOPPED THE FUEL SPILL. OUR DRIVER AND A AIR MED EMPLOYEE GRABBED THE SPILL KIT OFF OUR TRUCK TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED.  FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND PLACED SOME ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON THE SPILL AND ESCORTED OUR DRIVER AND THE AIR MED EMPLOYEE TO THE U OF U HOSPITAL ER TO HAVE THERE CLOTHES REMOVED AND GIVEN A SHOWER TO GET THE FUEL OFF THEM. OUR DRIVER ALSO HAD TO HAVE HIS EYE'S FLUSHED OUT (DRIVER WAS WEARING SAFETY GLASSES AT THE TIME OF SPILL).  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RELEASED THE SCENE TO THE HAZMAT CLEANUP COMPANY THAT WAS CALLED BY THE U OF U HOSPITAL TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.
column169: AS A COMPANY ALPHA TRANSPORT HAS MADE THE FOLLOWING CHANGE. INTERNAL VALVES ARE TO STAY CLOSED UNTIL PRODUCT HOSE IS HOOKED UP AND THE PRODUCT IS READY TO BE OFF-LOADED FROM THE TRAILER. IF OUR DRIVER WOULD HAVE FOLLOWED THIS STEP THE AMOUNT OF FUEL SPILLED WOULD HAVE BEEN REDUCED TO 5 TO 10 GALLONS.

column168: AT 8:30 AM CENTRAL TIME WE WERE NOTIFIED OF A POSSIBLE ROLL OVER INCIDENT NEAR MITCHELL, SD. WE CONTRACTED THE MITCHELL DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY AT 8:44AM AND THEY CONFIRMED THE INCIDENT. WE CONTRACTED DEPUTY MARK JENNESIS (SPELLING?) AT 8:53 AM AND HE CONFIRMED THAT AN ETHANOL PRODUCTS DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON HIGHWAY 37 AND A VEHICLE TRIED TO CROSS THE INTERSECTION AND WAS STRUCK BY OUR VEHICLE. HE INFORMED US THAT THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL, THAT OUR VEHICLE HAD BEEN SEPARATED AND THE TRAILER WAS UPSIDE DOWN IN THE DITCH. HE CONFIRMED THAT THE TRAILER WAS NOT LEAKING ANY PRODUCT. WHEN OUR FLEET MANGER ARRIVED ON THE SCENE, HE, WITH PERMISSION FROM SAFETY OFFICIALS ON THE SCENE, RELEASED THE CO2 INTO THE AIR SO THE TRAILER COULD BE UPRIGHTED AND REMOVED FROM THE SCENE. THERE WAS 40,000 POUNDS OF PRODUCT ON THE TRAILER WHEN IT ROLLED OVER. THE FLEET MANAGER RELEASED APPROXIMATELY HALF OF THE PRODUCT BACK INTO THE AIR. THE CARGO TRAILER DID NOT FAIL AND DID NOT RUPTURE DURING THE ACCIDENT. THE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED IN ORDER TO REMOVE THE CARGO TRAILER FROM THE SCENE.
column169: THIS ACCIDENT WAS NOT PREVENTABLE BY THE ETHANOL PRODUCTS DRIVER. THE OTHER VEHICLE COULD HAVE PREVENTED THE INCIDENT BY NOT PULLING OUT IN FRONT OF A MOVING VEHICLE.
