column168: BRENNTAG NORTHEAST DRIVER, RAY RIVERA WAS DELIVERING TO A CUSTOMER, AND HAD TO MOVE IBC'S UTILIZING AN ELECTRIC PALLET TO GET AT THE CUSTOMER'S PRODUCT. THE IBC'S WERE INTENDED FOR HIS FOLLOWING STOP. WHILE MOVING THE IBC, HE HEARD A "POP" AND RELEASED OF THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE IBC, WHICH WAS SODIUM HYDROXIDE 50%. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO CONTAIN THE LEAK BY PLACING ABSORBENT MATERIALS IN THE TRUCK AND SURROUNDING AREA. BRENNTAG NORTHEAST'S EMERGENCY CONTRACTOR, CURA, WAS CONTACTED, AT WHICH TIME A SPILL CLEANUP WAS INITIATED. AS IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THIS WAS A REPORTABLE QUANTITY, CURA, ON BRENNTAG NORTHEAST'S BEHALF, NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE NEW YORK DEPARTMENT OF CONSERVATION. CURA CONTRACTORS CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE IN THE TRAILER, CONCRETE PARKING AREA, AND STORM DRAIN. UPON CLEANUP AND REMEDIATION OF THE SITE, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE OUTLET VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE IBC HAD BECOME DISLODGED FROM THE IBC. WHILE WE ARE NOT COMPLETELY POSITIVE, BASED ON THE DAMAGE TO THE VALVE, IT IS ASSUMED THAT A FORK FROM THE ELECTRIC PALLET JACK, MAY HAVE INADVERTENTLY HIT THE OUTLET VALVE, CAUSING IT TO BE DISLODGED FROM THE IBC, THEREBY EMPTYING THE CONTENTS OF THE IBC INTO THE CONTENTS OF THE IBC INTO THE TRAILER, ONTO THE CONCRETE DRIVEWAY, AND INTO A STORM DRAIN

XPO LOGISTICS WAS TRANSPORTING AN INTERMODAL CONTAINER TO THE PORT OF NEW ORLEANS WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE 55-GALLON DRUM OF NITROMETHANE WAS LEAKING. APPARENTLY A CRACK WAS DETECTED AT THE BOTTOM O THE DRUM THAT WAS ALLOWING SOME NITROMETHANE TO LEAK FROM THE DRUM. THE CRACK APPEARED TO BE CAUSED BY A DEFECTIVE DRUM AND NOT FROM IMPROPER HANDLING OF THE DRUM. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF NITROMETHANE HAD LEAKED FROM THE 55-GALLON DRUM. THE PORT OF NEW ORLEANS CALLED THEIR IN HOUSE CONTRACT HAZMAT TEAM TO ADDRESS THE LEAK. THE DRUM WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN AND PLACED INSIDE AN OVERPACK DRUM. ABSORBENT PADS WERE USED TO ABSORB THE MATERIAL AND WAS ALSO PLACED INSIDE THE OVERPACK DRUM WITH THE LEAKING DRUM. A PUDDY SEALANT WAS APPLIED TO THE CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM TO PREVENT ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE FROM THE DRUM. THE DRUM AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PACKED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM AND SHIPPED BACK TO ANGUS CHEMICAL COMPANY FOR PROPER HANDLING. THERE WAS NO THREAT OR IMPACT TO THE ENVIRONMENT AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THE LEAKING DRUM. ONCE THE DRUM WAS EMPTIED AT THE ANGUS CHEMICAL COMPANY FACILITY, THE DRUM WAS SHIPPED BACK TO THE MANUFACTURER FOR TESTING TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE CRACK. INITIAL REPORTS FROM THE MANUFACTURER AND FROM THE STEEL SUPPLIER INDICATES THAT SOMETHING ABNORMAL OCCURRED IN THE STEEL MANUFACTURING PROCESS CAUSING THE STEEL TO BECOME TOO HARD AND THUS BEING SUSCEPTIBLE TO CRACKING. WE HAVE REQUESTED A WRITTEN REPORT AND ROOT CAUSE AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS FROM THE STEEL SUPPLIER BUT WE HAVE NOT RECEIVED IT AS OF THIS REPORT SUBMITTAL.
column169: XPO LOGISTICS DRAYAGE LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL. ONCE THE FINAL WRITTEN REPORT WITH ROOT CAUSE AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS FROM THE STEEL SUPPLIER IS RECEIVED, ANGUS WILL REVIEW THE REPORT AND MAKE ANY ADDITIONAL RECOMMENDATIONS AND/OR SEE THAT THE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS ARE COMPLETED IN A TIMELY MANNER.

column168: THE DRIVER OF MY PICKUP WENT TO ELDORADO, IL SOUTHERN FS TO TAKE DELIVERY OF 2 ANHYDROUS AMMONIA AT ABOUT 6AM. THE DRIVER, MATT WALKER, THEN PROCEEDED BACK TO FIELD THAT WAS LOCATED JUST NORTH OF HARRISBURG. ABOUT 3 MILES N OF HARRISBURG ON RT 34, MATT SAID THAT THE BACK TANK LOST CONTROL AND WHIPPED THE 1ST TANK AND TRUCK THE BOTH TANKS CAME UNDONE FROM TRUCK. MATT CALLED TO THE FIELD TRACTOR DRIVER AT ABOUT 6:30 AM ON JUNE 29TH THEN HE CALLED ME. I WAS AT THE FARM SHOP WHICH WAS ABOUT 2 MILE N OF ACCIDENT. UPON ARRIVING AT SCENE, VAPOR WAS RELEASING FARM TANK #2 GOING FROM N TO E ACCESS RT 34. I CALLED 911, ELDORADO FIRE DEPT RESPONDED. MY FIELD HAND AND MATT WERE ON THE S OF ACCIDENT. I WAS ON THE N. CONTROLLED TRAFFIC UNTIL EFD ARRIVED. THEY ABLE TO CLOSE THE VALVE ON TANK WHERE THE RELEASE WAS COMING FROM ABOUT 20 MIN  AFTER ARRIVE RT 34 WAS CLOSED TIL 11 AM. SOUTHERN FS PEOPLE ASSISTED. VERNAL WRECKER OF MARION RESPONDED RT 34 WAS THEN CLEARED OPEN FOR TRAFFIC.
column169: MATT WALKER HAD ALREADY MOVED ANHYDROUS TANKS LAST YEAR AND WE HAD TRAINING ON PROPER HOOKING AND TRANSPORT OF SUCH TANKS. ILL DOT EVEN STOPPED AND INSPECTED US LAST YEAR WITH NO TICKETS ISSUED. MATT HAD SUCCESSFULLY TRANSPORTED TANKS ALL YEAR (2019) THIS (JUNE 29) WAS OUR LAST DAY FOR ANHYDROUS APPLICATION. SO, THERE IS NOTHING COMES MY ATTENTION THAT COULD OR SHOULD HAVE BEEN DIFFERENT.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: ON THE MORNING OF JUNE 25TH 2019, TRAILER #53616V ARRIVED AT OUR VANDALIA, OH TERMINAL. UPON ARRIVAL, SMOKE WAS SEEN COMING FROM THE TRAILER. FIREFIGHTERS ARRIVED ON SCENE SHORTLY AFTER BEING CONTACTED. THE FIREFIGHTERS THEN CALLED A HAZMAT CREW TO THE SCENE. THE HAZMAT CREW DETERMINED THAT IT WAS SAFE TO OPEN THE TRAILER DOOR. WHEN THE TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED, THE FIRE WAS ALREADY OUT, AND FLAMES WERE NEVER ACTUALLY SEEN BY ANY EMPLOYEES OR FIRE PERSONNEL. THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF USED BATTERIES THAT WERE BEING SHIPPED FROM BURNLEY TO PARTS FOR CANS. FROM INVESTIGATION WITH THE COSIGNEE IT WAS STATED THAT THESE WERE USED BATTERIES FROM MOTORIZED SHOPPING CARTS, PURCHASED FROM A NATIONAL RETAILER. BURNLEY WAS THEN TO TAKE OFF ALL BATTERY CONNECTORS PRIOR TO SHIPPING TO PARTS FOR CARTS. ALL CABLES WERE NOT TAKEN OFF PROPERLY AND DURING SHIPMENT THE WIRES FROM THE BATTERIES WERE ABLE TO MAKE CONTACT WITH THE POSTS RESULTING IN THE FIRE. THIS FAILURE WAS NOT VISIBLE TO OUR DRIVER AT THE TIME OF PICK-UP.
column169: IN THIS CASE, TO PREVENT RECURRENCE, ALL BATTERY WIRES NEED TO BE REMOVED PRIOR TO SHIPPING REFURBISHED BATTERIES CENTRAL TRANSPORT HAS SINCE AVOIDED PICKING UP AND TRANSPORTING SHIPMENTS OF THE SAME COMMODITY. WE ALSO HAVE AVOIDED PICKING UP FROM THE SAME VENDOR INVOLVED.

column168: During initial loading operation driver noticed a leak from the center of CTMV. Loading immediately stopped. Material was trans-loaded to another CTMV. Inspection revealed gaskets were defective causing leak on CTMV. Gaskets were replaced, CTMV pressure tested past test. Shipper facility's personnel cleaned up material and process properly.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Driver misjudged the turn while attempting to enter the parking lot of Kroger 377 in Forest, VA. The trailer's number four loading head caught a fire hydrant near the entry way and pulled  it from the ground. Once the loading head and airlines were damaged we lost approximately  5 gallons from the wet line. The police and fire department responded. The police did not file a  report and the fire department assisted our driver in cleaning up the spilled product. No soil or  storm drain contamination, the spill was confined to the asphalt area in the parking lot.   ETC shop foreman responded to assist the driver with the damaged trailer. Upon arrival the  trailer airlines were repaired and the decision was made to unload all of the product except for  compartment four, which contained 1000 gallons of Premium. When the shop foreman opened  the belly valve door product was released from the damaged compartment because the belly valve  was open. This created a second spill of approximately 20 gallons, which approximately 6 gallons  entered the storm drain and was released into the retention pond. Action Environmental managed a  clean up crew to the site.  Spill was reported to VADEQ.
column169: The driver was placed back into training and an intervention was started.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Driver hooked up to next regular compartment on trailer to unload. Driver had forgotten to hook the  ground fitting back up. Driver then pulled the handle and released regular gasoline onto the ground. Action Environmental managed the cleanup. According to AOTC Environmental and Alachua County Environmental approx. 30 gallons of regular gasoline were spilled with 8-10 gallons reaching the grass drainage area. Contaminated soil was removed
column169: Driver was suspended for one day and placed back into training.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Broken Component or Device
column168: CN TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT EMPLOYEE REPORTED LIQUID COMING DOWN THE SIDE OF GATX 5839 (SULFURIC ACID / UN1832) DURING OPERATIONS AT THE CN BATON ROUGE YARD, BATON ROUGE, LA. ALL APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED, TANK CAR ISOLATED. CN'S RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED NOTING THE MANWAY BOLTS IN THE DOWN POSITION. THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE PROPERLY INSTALLED AND TIGHTENED. THE FRANGIBLE DISK WAS ALSO FOUND TO BE BLOWN. THE FRANGIBLE DISK WAS REPLACED. THE EXTERIOR OF THE RAILCAR WAS DECONTAMINATED. THE RAILCAR WAS RELEASED BACK TO TRANSPORTATION.

During unloading preparation the consignee's provided a storage tank for the shipment. During unloading consignee's receiving tank overfilled due to not having enough space for the shipment. Unloading immediately stopped and Consignee's personnel redirected the driver to another storage tank to complete the unloading. Consignee's personnel cleaned up and process properly.
column169: Reinforce consignee's unloading preparation training to ensure tank capacity is verified for the shipment to be unloaded as well as verify high level sensors in working condition.

column168: During the unloading phase of trailer, employee was attempting to unload a pallet of freight with a forklift, the forklift blades were protruding past the pallet and punctured a box in front of the pallet. Contact was made at the bottom side of the box putting a 1.0 inch long puncture in the box that caused a puncture to the inner packaging. Inner packaging was then taken out placed in a position to where the material would not leak further. All spillage of material was confined to immediate area for cleanup.
column169: Proper follow-up and retraining will be completed with employee.

column168: CTMV driver reported once CTMV was loaded by shipper personnel, they noticed leaking of product from center unload flange into the shipper's containment area. Shipper unloaded CTMV. column169: Closer supervision by loading personnel for issues including product leaks during loading process.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On 06/18/2019, 0107 ET, ERTS received a call from XPO Logistics - XCA regarding a hazardous cargo release. It was reported that due to a forklift puncture, (1) 1150 gaylord containing UN1133 3, PG II "Remabond Brush Cement" released an approximate 5 gallons onto the tail of the trailer floor. ERTS reviewed the SDS with XPO who confirmed adequate ventilation and that the terminal had the proper PPE and absorbents to complete the cleanup. All waste will remain on site located in the terminal's OS&D.

On 06/19/2019, at 0633 ET, ERTS was notified by of XPO (XAU) regarding a cargo release. According to the caller, approximately 1-cup of UN1866, Resin solution, "Crystalac" released to a dock floor from a (1) 5-gallon plastic pail due to a puncture caused by a nail on a skid. The caller indicated the release was contained to the dock floor. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined terminal personnel were capable of cleaning the release with the use of appropriate PPE. Terminal has containerized waste into a (1) 10-gallon DM to be staged in OS&D. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release.

column168: DUTCH PROPANE, LLC CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE (BOBTAIL) WAS HEADING SOUTHEAST ON TOWN STREET (RT 82) IN EAST HADDAM ON ITS WAY TO MAKE A REGULAR ROUTED PROPANE DELIVERY WHEN AN ONCOMING CAR LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE AND TRAVELED INTO CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE'S LANE STRIKING THE CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE. THE CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE WAS ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE AND CAME TO REST AT THE BOTTOM OF HUNGERFORD RD. LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENTS WERE DISPATCHED AS WELL STATE POLICE AND DEEP. THE OFFICE OF DUTCH PROPANE, LLC CALLED IN A THIRD PARTY EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM, DISPATCHED THROUGH LIBERTY PROPANE TO STOP THE LEAK ON THE VEHICLE'S PIPING & PUMP THE PROPANE OVER TO ANOTHER DUTCH PROPANE VEHICLE BROUGHT TO SITE IN ORDER FOR DAMAGED VEHICLE TO BE TOWED. THE TRUCK WAS ROLLED BACK ONTO ITS WHEELS, HOSES AND COMPRESSOR WERE HOOKED UP TO EVAC PLUG ON BOTTOM OF PROPANE TANK. ALL THE LIQUID WAS PUMPED OFF THE TRUCK. THE ROADWAY WAS OPENED BACK UP TO TRAFFIC. THE TRUCK WAS THEN TOWED DOWN THE ROAD TO A NEARBY FIELD WHERE IT WAS SAFE TO HAVE THE REMAINING VAPOR FLARED OFF. THE TANK WAS DENTED AND IT WAS DEEMED BY DEEP THAT IT NO LONGER MEETS DOT CODE AND NEEDED TO BE FLARED. SET UP FLARED. SET UP FLARE AND BURNED OFF ALL THE VAPOR. TRUCK WAS TOWED AWAY.
